<br>
And to me when you can't be right you should try to be fair. <p><CENTER><A HREF="http://ak.lonelygamer.com">
<IMG SRC="http://www.plattsflello.com/ryn.gif" BORDER=0></A></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/bemarr.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=misty>Misty</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://users.bigpond.com/dwmac/eq12.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 216<br> <font color=#E9D756>(1/10/02 4:08:44 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2888.topic&index=63>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: NBG is BS!</span><hr size=1> Actually, I think it is safe to say either system will govern the loot rules depending on the groupleader and the agreement of particulars with his grp beforehand. Often I have joined a group at a particular spawn and the loot rules went &quot;alpha cash /random rare&quot; and I have coveted a rare that reputedly dropped from that camp. And I have abided by the rule and joined the group. <br>
<br>
Group rules are a flexible thing and can change, I have had no qualms letting a Cleric loot his Velious dropped spell from a Wurm (Celestial Healing) and a wizard looting his Lure spell: I personally came hoping to loot my own &quot;spell&quot; but unfortunately never have. Would I retro-actively seize the cleric's spell scroll(if it were possible)? I have been in KC where rares are 'very' rare, nbg always applied in the groups. I really stood every prospect of gaining nil items but I stayed and played EQ anyway. And I have joined 1 Hate raid, and 1 Naggie raid and accepted the loot system as explained when I came aboard then, as well: I can take comfort from observing that I percieve the players I am presenting to as &quot;okay&quot; people on 1st impressions. I will gauge my appraisal of my new friends as we get to know each other more and see each other in game more frequently. What applies to the loot rules is generally covered by the drop, and the grp situation: in a raid, your grp is just one of possibly 5+ full groups and the loot system instatement involves a lengthy process of  organisation. Generally the only common channel of communication for broadcasting loot rules to the raid is /ooc, /guild, or chatroom (meaning log and get the raid rules briefing). Most classes will know which mob has their Planar pieces and the /random system for the class nodrop is generally accepted before the apportionment of the items is commenced. (from what I understand, the rules are fairly standard for subsequent raids)<br>
To argue that one system ought be completely abolished in preference to another simply does not get around the circumnstance of a particular situation. NBG is fair, u wait for your pce and it is yours, ffa gives you a chance, and can take your chance away too. Ultimately you choose to accept either way before you see your item drop: I abide by that agreement. If I happen to become grp leader, I always get a consensus or a majority agreement and accommodate the group loot preferences: I will count the represented classes and give a casting vote to the class which uses the drop provided none has it, if they are 2-3 then they can have the drop awarded amongst them by their higher preference, generally a class (tank/hybrid/priest/caster)will be in agreement how this shall be done; if they cannot agree I will arbitrate it(hence the majority vote), the guy who has 'x' or as good is just a bit selfish &quot;You 2 /random it(their own is crap)&quot;, if the 1st guy who has 'x' objects, too bad.. I can generally get an opinion from the rest of the grp (including my own)as well but you better believe the final call: most of the group can agree. <br>
<br>
If I am harrassed, very unlikely, a group member is ejected, quite simple really: &quot;You can leave if you disagree that strongly&quot; and &quot;Keep sooking and I will eject you&quot;. This sort of thing is common in groups, I am not always leader so I put a fair degree of belief in the grp system. That system is the only real decider.<br>
<br>
